[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] 1903 was the third year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the still-new American League.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in fifth place with a record or 65–71 (.478), 25 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The 1903 Tigers outscored their opponents 567 to 539.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 224,523, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] 1904 was the fourth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 62–90 (.408), 32 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] They played ten tie games, which is the major league record.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The 1904 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 627 to 505.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 177,796, seventh out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] In the year before Ty Cobb's arrival, pitcher George Mullin had a higher batting average than any of the team's regulars at .290.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] 1905 was the fifth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in third place with a record of 79–74 (.516), 151⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers posted a run differential of -97, the lowest ever by a team with a winning record, breaking the previous record of -81 held by the 1882 Detroit Wolverines; the Tigers lost 48 games by 3 or more runs.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 602 to 512, the largest negative run differential ever for a Major League team with a winning record.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 193,384, eighth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The **1911 Detroit Tigers** had a record of 89–65 and finished in second place in the American League, 131⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] They outscored their opponents 831–776, and drew 484,988 fans to Bennett Park (4th of 8 teams in attendance).
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The 1911 Detroit Tigers opened the season with a phenomenal 21–2 record.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers set the modern record for home wins to start the season, 12–0, and were 51–25 at home but 38–40 on the road.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] They were in first place in the American League every day except one until August 3, 1911.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] After going 59–24, the wheels fell off as the team lost 20 of 30 games in July and were 23–43 in the second half.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers lost 20 of 30 games in July and ended up 131⁄2 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The 1911 Tigers had two of the best batters in baseball in Ty Cobb and Sam Crawford.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] Crawford was not far behind, ranking in the top three in the AL in batting average (.378), slugging (.438), hits (217), total bases (302), and RBIs (115).
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] The team ranked second best in the American League in runs scored but the pitching staff's earned run average of 3.73 was the second worst in the league—a full point above the league leading Red Sox' team ERA of 2.74.
[src:1911-detroit-tigers-season/1911-detroit-tigers-season] Playing in Bennett Field, with its 8,500-seat wooden grandstand, their home attendance for the entire season was 484,988.
